    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1762385548,
    "last_edit_date" : 1762385548,
    "creation_date" : 1761823243,
    "answer_id" : 79804700,
    "question_id" : 35231291,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I had a Kotlin program that worked successfully at displaying Unicode emojis, etc. in the IntelliJ Idea console using JDK 21.</p>\n<p>When I more-or-less-simultaneously upgraded from:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Idea 2025.1.4.1 to Idea 2025.2.4</li>\n<li>JDK 21 to JDK 25</li>\n<li>Gradle 8.8 to 9.1.0</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I eventually noticed that this had stopped working correctly, and the emojis were instead appearing in the console as question mark characters.</p>\n<p>I tried most of the suggestions shown in this and similar Stack Overflow questions (sprinkling <code>-Dconsole.encoding=UTF-8</code> and <code>-Dfile.encoding=UTF-8</code> in various locations in Idea's config files, Gradle's config files, experimenting with JAVA_TOOLS_OPTIONS, etc.), but nothing worked to fix the problem.</p>\n<p>Eventually, I realized that for some reason, the encoding of my System.out in my Kotlin program had changed. I'm not sure whether this was due to upgrading Idea, Gradle, or the JDK. Still, it was clear that although files were still being written as UTF-8, output to System.out was instead being written as my system's default encoding (which was not UTF-8). This was what was causing the problems in the console output.</p>\n<p>The following code (adapted from <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28567208/how-can-i-change-the-standard-out-to-utf-8-in-java\">this question</a>), executed as the first thing that my program did, fixed this problem and allowed the IntelliJ Idea console to display the emojis correctly again.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-kotlin prettyprint-override\"><code>/**\n * Set the standard output stream to use UTF-8 encoding.\n * This is necessary to support Unicode (emojis, etc.) appearing in the IntelliJ Idea console.\n */\nprivate fun setStdOutToUtf8() {\n    try {\n        System.setOut(PrintStream(FileOutputStream(FileDescriptor.out), true, &quot;UTF-8&quot;))\n    } catch (_: UnsupportedEncodingException) {\n        throw InternalError(&quot;VM does not support mandatory encoding UTF-8&quot;)\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Note that having the program output UTF-8 may work OK in the IntelliJ Idea console, but may not work correctly if the program is invoked from an ordinary  command shell, which will likely have its encoding set to the system default. For my usage, this was not an issue (I am only invoking my program from within IDEA, at least for now), but it may be for those who are trying to write command-line utility programs.</p>\n<p>If anybody can establish which of these upgrades (Idea, Gradle, or the JDK) was responsible for breaking this, I would love to know.</p>\n"
  } ],
